  "prompt": "How do conjugations in Greek, Latin and Sanskrit compare to each other?",
  "response": "Greek, Latin, and Sanskrit are all Indo-European languages, and their conjugation systems have both similarities and differences due to their common ancestry and individual linguistic evolution. Here\u2019s a comparative overview:\n\n### Greek Conjugation\n\nGreek verbs are categorized primarily into thematic and athematic types. They conjugate according to tense (present, imperfect, future, aorist, perfect, pluperfect), mood (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, optative), voice (active, middle, passive), and person (first, second, third in singular and plural). \n\n#### Example (Present Indicative Active of \"\u03bb\u03cd\u03c9\" - \"I release\"):\n- **\u03bb\u03cd\u03c9** (I release)\n- **\u03bb\u03cd\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2** (you release)\n- **\u03bb\u03cd\u03b5\u03b9** (he/she/it releases)\n- **\u03bb\u03cd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd** (we release)\n- **\u03bb\u03cd\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5** (you all release)\n- **\u03bb\u03cd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9** (they release)\n\n### Latin Conjugation\n\nLatin verbs are divided into four conjugations and also organized by tense (present, imperfect, future, perfect, pluperfect, future perfect), mood (indicative, subjunctive, imperative), voice (active, passive), and person (first, second, third in singular and plural). \n\n#### Example (Present Indicative Active of \"amare\" - \"to love\"):\n- **amo** (I love)\n- **amas** (you love)\n- **amat** (he/she/it loves)\n- **amamus** (we love)\n- **amatis** (you all love)\n- **amant** (they love)\n\n### Sanskrit Conjugation\n\nSanskrit verbs are categorized into ten classes based on their stem formation and conjugated according to tense-systems (present, imperfect, future, aorist), mood (indicative, imperative, optative, subjunctive), voice (active, passive, middle), and person (first, second, third in singular, dual, and plural). It also includes a complex system of participles and verbal nouns.\n\n#### Example (Present Indicative Active of \"\u092a\u091a\u094d\" - \"to cook\"):\n- **\u092a\u091a\u093e\u092e\u093f** (I cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u0938\u093f** (you cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u0924\u093f** (he/she/it cooks)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u093e\u0935\u0903** (we two cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u093e\u092e\u0903** (we cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u0925\u0903** (you two cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u0925** (you all cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u0924\u0903** (they two cook)\n- **\u092a\u091a\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f** (they cook)\n\n### Comparison\n\n1. **Tenses**: All three languages feature multiple tenses including present, aorist/past, future, and perfect/pluperfect. Latin and Greek have an imperfect tense while Sanskrit has an imperfect but additionally employs the injunctive mood, especially in Vedic Sanskrit.\n\n2. **Moods**: All three languages have indicative, imperative, and subjunctive/optative moods. Greek includes the optative separately, while Sanskrit combines subjunctive and optative moods.\n\n3. **Voice**: Greek and Sanskrit include active, middle, and passive voices, while Latin primarily uses active and passive, with some deponent verbs which are middle voice in meaning but passive in form.\n\n4. **Number**: Sanskrit uniquely includes a dual number, whereas Greek and Latin stick to singular and plural forms.\n\n5. **Stem Formation**: Sanskrit's conjugation classes are highly complex and based on specific stem formations. Greek and Latin have simpler conjugation systems, usually based on thematic vowels or specific endings.\n\n6. **Inflection**: All three languages rely heavily on inflection, changing the endings of words to indicate different tenses, moods, voices, and numbers.\n\nWhile these languages share structural similarities typical of Indo-European languages, each developed unique features that reflect their histories and uses.",
